[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] A **bar chart** or **bar graph** is a chart or graph that presents categorical data with rectangular bars with heights or lengths proportional to the values that they represent.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] The bars can be plotted vertically or horizontally.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] A vertical bar chart is sometimes called a **column chart** and has been identified as the prototype of charts.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] A bar graph shows comparisons among discrete categories.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] One axis of the chart shows the specific categories being compared, and the other axis represents a measured value.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] Some bar graphs present bars clustered or stacked in groups of more than one, showing the values of more than one measured variable.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] Many sources consider William Playfair (1759–1824) to have invented the bar chart and the *Exports and Imports of Scotland to and from different parts for one Year from Christmas 1780 to Christmas 1781* graph from his *The Commercial and Political Atlas* to be the first bar chart in history.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] Diagrams of the velocity of a constantly accelerating object against time published in *The Latitude of Forms* (attributed to Jacobus de Sancto Martino or, perhaps, to Nicole Oresme) about 300 years before can be interpreted as "proto bar charts".
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] Bar graphs/charts provide a visual presentation of categorical data.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] Categorical data is a grouping of data into discrete groups, such as months of the year, age group, shoe sizes, and animals.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] These categories are usually qualitative.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] In a column (vertical) bar chart, categories appear along the horizontal axis and the height of the bar corresponds to the value of each category.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] Bar charts have a discrete domain of categories, and are usually scaled so that all the data can fit on the chart.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] When there is no natural ordering of the categories being compared, bars on the chart may be arranged in any order.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] Bar charts arranged from highest to lowest incidence are called Pareto charts.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] In many cases it is considered correct to use zero as the value at the end of each bar opposite to the end that indicates the data value, because using a non-zero value can make values that are relatively similar have deceptively different bar lengths.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] However, sometimes this approach is not appropriate or not feasible, such as with temperatures in Celsius or Fahrenheit where zero is a somewhat arbitrary value, and with logarithmic charts where "log(0)" would be infinitely far away.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] Bar graphs can also be used for more complex comparisons of data with grouped (or "clustered") bar charts, and stacked bar charts.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] In **grouped (clustered) bar charts**, for each categorical group there are two or more bars color-coded to represent a particular grouping.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] For example, a business owner with two stores might make a grouped bar chart with different colored bars to represent each store: the horizontal axis would show the months of the year and the vertical axis would show revenue.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] Alternatively, **Stacked bar charts** (also known as **Composite bar charts**) stack bars on top of each other so that the height of the resulting stack shows the combined result.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] Unlike a grouped bar chart where each factor is displayed next to another, each with their own bar, the stacked bar chart displays multiple data points stacked in a single row or column.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] This may, for instance, take the form of uniform height bars charting a time series with internal stacked colours indicating the percentage participation of a sub-type of data.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] Another example would be a time series displaying total numbers, with internal colors indicating participation in the total by sub-types.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] Stacked bar charts are not suited to data sets having both positive and negative values.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] Grouped bar charts usually present the information in the same order in each grouping.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] Stacked bar charts present the information in the same sequence on each bar.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] Variable-width bar charts, sometimes abbreviated *variwide* (bar) charts, are bar charts having bars with non-uniform widths.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] Roles of the vertical and horizontal axes may be reversed, depending on the desired application.
[src:plotly-python/bar-chart] Examples of variable-width bar charts are shown at Wikimedia Commons.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] In addition, **Narrative visualization** is a method that uses visual elements such as charts, graphs, maps and the like to convey data or information.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] This approach blends data analysis, storytelling, and visualization to present information through structured narrative flows- *using visuals not just to present statistics, but to tell a story through data*.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Its goal is to help people identify trends, patterns, and relationships in data through a compelling story-driven visual experience.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Emerging technologies like virtual, augmented and mixed reality have the potential to make information visualization more immersive, intuitive, interactive and easily manipulable and thus enhance the user's visual perception and cognition.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Effective data visualization is well-sourced, appropriately contextualized, and presented in a simple, uncluttered manner.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The underlying data is accurate and up-to-date to ensure insights are reliable.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Graphical items are well-chosen and aesthetically appealing, with shapes, colors and other visual elements used deliberately in a meaningful and non-distracting manner.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The visuals are accompanied by supporting texts.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Verbal and graphical components complement each other to ensure clear, quick and memorable understanding.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Effective information visualization is aware of the needs and expertise level of the target audience.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Data scientists, analysts and data mining specialists use data visualization to check data quality, find errors, unusual gaps, missing values, clean data, explore the structures and features of data, and assess outputs of data-driven models.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization can be part of *data storytelling*, where they are paired with a narrative structure, to contextualize the analyzed data and communicate insights gained from analyzing it to convince the audience into making a decision or taking action.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization is interdisciplinary, it incorporates principles found in descriptive statistics, visual communication, graphic design, cognitive science and, interactive computer graphics and human-computer interaction.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Since effective visualization requires design skills, statistical skills and computing skills, it is both an art and a science.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Visual analytics combines statistical data analysis, data and information visualization, and human analytical reasoning through interactive visual interfaces to help users reach conclusions, gain actionable insights and make informed decisions which are otherwise difficult for computers to do.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Research into how people read and misread types of visualizations helps to determine what types and features of visualizations are most understandable and effective.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Unintentionally poor or intentionally misleading and deceptive visualizations can function as powerful tools which disseminate misinformation, manipulate public perception and divert public opinion.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Thus data visualization literacy has become an important component of data and information literacy in the information age akin to the roles played by textual, mathematical and visual literacy in the past.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The field of data and information visualization has emerged "from research in human–computer interaction, computer science, graphics, visual design, psychology, photography and business methods.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] It is increasingly applied as a critical component in scientific research, digital libraries, data mining, financial data analysis, market studies, manufacturing production control, and drug discovery".
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization presumes that "visual representations and interaction techniques take advantage of the human eye's broad bandwidth pathway into the mind to allow users to see, explore, and understand large amounts of information at once.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Data analysis is an indispensable part of all applied research and problem solving in industry.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Among these approaches, information visualization, or visual data analysis, is the most reliant on the cognitive skills of human analysts, and allows the discovery of unstructured actionable insights that are limited only by human imagination and creativity.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The analyst does not have to learn any sophisticated methods to be able to interpret the visualizations of the data.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Information visualization is also a hypothesis generation scheme, which can be, and is typically followed by more analytical or formal analysis, such as statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] To communicate information clearly and efficiently, data visualization uses statistical graphics, plots, information graphics and other tools.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Numerical data may be encoded using dots, lines, or bars, to visually communicate a quantitative message.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Effective visualization helps users analyze and reason about data and evidence.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] It makes complex data more accessible, understandable, and usable, but can also be reductive.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Users may have particular analytical tasks, such as making comparisons or understanding causality, and the design principle of the graphic (i.e., showing comparisons or showing causality) follows the task.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Tables are generally used where users will look up a specific measurement, while charts of various types are used to show patterns or relationships in the data for one or more variables.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization refers to the techniques used to communicate data or information by encoding it as visual objects (e.g., points, lines, or bars) contained in graphics.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The goal is to communicate information clearly and efficiently to users.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] It is one of the steps in data analysis or data science.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] According to Vitaly Friedman (2008) the "main goal of data visualization is to communicate information clearly and effectively through graphical means.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] It doesn't mean that data visualization needs to look boring to be functional or extremely sophisticated to look beautiful.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] To convey ideas effectively, both aesthetic form and functionality need to go hand in hand, providing insights into a rather sparse and complex data set by communicating its key aspects in a more intuitive way.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Yet designers often fail to achieve a balance between form and function, creating gorgeous data visualizations which fail to serve their main purpose — to communicate information".
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Wattenberg suggested that an ideal visualization should not only communicate clearly, but stimulate viewer engagement and attention.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is closely related to information graphics, information visualization, scientific visualization, exploratory data analysis and statistical graphics.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] In the new millennium, data visualization has become an active area of research, teaching and development.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] (2002), it has united scientific and information visualization.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] In the commercial environment data visualization is often referred to as dashboards.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Infographics are another very common form of data visualization.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Edward Tufte has explained that users of information displays are executing particular *analytical tasks* such as making comparisons.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The *design principle* of the information graphic should support the analytical task.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] As William Cleveland and Robert McGill show, different graphical elements accomplish this more or less effectively.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] For example, dot plots and bar charts outperform pie charts.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] In his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, Edward Tufte defines 'graphical displays' and principles for effective graphical display in the following passage: "Excellence in statistical graphics consists of complex ideas communicated with clarity, precision, and efficiency.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] For example, the Minard diagram shows the losses suffered by Napoleon's army in the 1812–1813 period.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Six variables are plotted: the size of the army, its location on a two-dimensional surface (x and y), time, the direction of movement, and temperature.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The line width illustrates a comparison (size of the army at points in time), while the temperature axis suggests a cause of the change in army size.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] This multivariate display on a two-dimensional surface tells a story that can be grasped immediately while identifying the source data to build credibility.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Not applying these principles may result in misleading graphs, distorting the message, or supporting an erroneous conclusion.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] According to Tufte, chartjunk refers to the extraneous interior decoration of the graphic that does not enhance the message or gratuitous three-dimensional or perspective effects.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Needlessly separating the explanatory key from the image itself, requiring the eye to travel back and forth from the image to the key, is a form of "administrative debris." The ratio of "data to ink" should be maximized, erasing non-data ink where feasible.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The Congressional Budget Office summarized several best practices for graphical displays in a June 2014 presentation.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] These included: a) Knowing your audience; b) Designing graphics that can stand alone outside the report's context; and c) Designing graphics that communicate the key messages in the report.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] For greatest efficiency and simplicity of design and user experience, this readability is enhanced through the use of bijective mapping in that design of the image elements - where the mapping of representational element to data variable is unique.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Kosara (2007) also identifies the need for a visualisation to be "recognisable as a visualisation and not appear to be something else".
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] He also states that recognisability and readability may not always be required in all types of visualisation e.g.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] "informative art" (which would still meet all three above criteria but might not look like a visualisation) or "artistic visualisation" (which similarly is still based on non-visual data to create an image, but may not be readable or recognisable).
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Ranking: Categorical subdivisions are ranked in ascending or descending order, such as a ranking of sales performance (the *measure*) by sales persons (the *category*, with each sales person a *categorical subdivision*) during a single period.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used to show the comparison across the sales persons.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Part-to-whole: Categorical subdivisions are measured as a ratio to the whole (i.e., a percentage out of 100%).
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] A pie chart or bar chart can show the comparison of ratios, such as the market share represented by competitors in a market.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Deviation: Categorical subdivisions are compared against a reference, such as a comparison of actual vs. budget expenses for several departments of a business for a given time period.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart can show comparison of the actual versus the reference amount.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Frequency distribution: Shows the number of observations of a particular variable for given interval, such as the number of years in which the stock market return is between intervals such as 0–10%, 11–20%, etc.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] A histogram, a type of bar chart, may be used for this analysis.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] A boxplot helps visualize key statistics about the distribution, such as median, quartiles, outliers, etc.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Correlation: Comparison between observations represented by two variables (X,Y) to determine if they tend to move in the same or opposite directions.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] For example, plotting unemployment (X) and inflation (Y) for a sample of months.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] A scatter plot is typically used for this message.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Nominal comparison: Comparing categorical subdivisions in no particular order, such as the sales volume by product code.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used for this comparison.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Geographic or geospatial: Comparison of a variable across a map or layout, such as the unemployment rate by state or the number of persons on the various floors of a building.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Analysts reviewing a set of data may consider whether some or all of the messages and graphic types above are applicable to their task and audience.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The process of trial and error to identify meaningful relationships and messages in the data is part of exploratory data analysis.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] A human can distinguish differences in line length, shape, orientation, distances, and color (hue) readily without significant processing effort; these are referred to as "pre-attentive attributes".
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] For example, it may require significant time and effort ("attentive processing") to identify the number of times the digit "5" appears in a series of numbers; but if that digit is different in size, orientation, or color, instances of the digit can be noted quickly through pre-attentive processing.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Compelling graphics take advantage of pre-attentive processing and attributes and the relative strength of these attributes.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] For example, since humans can more easily process differences in line length than surface area, it may be more effective to use a bar chart (which takes advantage of line length to show comparison) rather than pie charts (which use surface area to show comparison).
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Almost all data visualizations are created for human consumption.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Knowledge of human perception and cognition is necessary when designing intuitive visualizations.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Cognition refers to processes in human beings like perception, attention, learning, memory, thought, concept formation, reading, and problem solving.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Human visual processing is efficient in detecting changes and making comparisons between quantities, sizes, shapes and variations in lightness.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] When properties of symbolic data are mapped to visual properties, humans can browse through large amounts of data efficiently.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] It is estimated that 2/3 of the brain's neurons can be involved in visual processing.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Proper visualization provides a different approach to show potential connections, relationships, etc. which are not as obvious in non-visualized quantitative data.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Visualization can become a means of data exploration.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Studies have shown individuals used on average 19% less cognitive resources, and 4.5% better able to recall details when comparing data visualization with text.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] There is no comprehensive history of data visualization.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] There are no accounts that span the entire development of visual thinking and visual representation of data, and which collate the contributions of disparate disciplines.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Michael Friendly and Daniel Denis of York University are engaged in a project that attempts to provide a comprehensive history of visualization.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is not a modern development.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Since prehistory, stellar data, or information such as location of stars were visualized on the walls of caves (such as those found in Lascaux Cave in Southern France) since the Pleistocene era.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Physical artefacts such as Mesopotamian clay tokens (5500 BC), Inca quipus (2600 BC) and Marshall Islands stick charts (n.d.) can also be considered as visualizing quantitative information.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The first documented data visualization can be tracked back to 1160 B.C. with the Turin Papyrus Map which accurately illustrates the distribution of geological resources and provides information about quarrying of those resources.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Such maps can be categorized as thematic cartography, which is a type of data visualization that presents and communicates specific data and information through a geographical illustration designed to show a particular theme connected with a specific geographic area.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Earliest documented forms of data visualization were various thematic maps from different cultures and ideograms and hieroglyphs that provided and allowed interpretation of information illustrated.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] For example, Linear B tablets of Mycenae provided a visualization of information regarding Late Bronze Age era trades in the Mediterranean.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The idea of coordinates was used by ancient Egyptian surveyors in laying out towns, earthly and heavenly positions were located by something akin to latitude and longitude at least by 200 BC, and the map projection of a spherical Earth into latitude and longitude by Claudius Ptolemy [c.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] 165] in Alexandria would serve as reference standards until the 14th century.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The invention of paper and parchment allowed further development of visualizations.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] One graph from the 10th or possibly 11th century is an illustration of planetary movements, used in an appendix of a textbook in monastery schools.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The graph apparently was meant to represent a plot of the inclinations of the planetary orbits as a function of the time.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] For this purpose, the zone of the zodiac was represented on a plane with a horizontal line divided into thirty parts as the time or longitudinal axis.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The vertical axis designates the width of the zodiac.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The horizontal scale appears to have been chosen for each planet individually for the periods cannot be reconciled.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The accompanying text refers only to the amplitudes.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The curves are apparently not related in time.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] By the 16th century, techniques and instruments for precise observation and measurement of physical quantities, and geographic and celestial position were well-developed (for example, a "wall quadrant" constructed by Tycho Brahe [1546–1601], covering an entire wall in his observatory).
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Particularly important were the development of triangulation and other methods to determine mapping locations accurately.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Very early, the measure of time led scholars to develop innovative way of visualizing the data (e.g.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Lorenz Codomann in 1596, Johannes Temporarius in 1596).
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Mathematicians René Descartes and Pierre de Fermat developed analytic geometry and two-dimensional coordinate system which heavily influenced the practical methods of displaying and calculating values.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Fermat and Blaise Pascal's work on statistics and probability theory laid the groundwork for what we now conceptualize as data.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] These developments helped William Playfair, who saw potential for graphical communication of quantitative data, to generate and develop graphical methods of statistics.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] In 1786, Playfair published the first presentation graphics.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Jacques Bertin used quantitative graphs to represent information "intuitively, clearly, accurately, and efficiently".
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] John Tukey and Edward Tufte pushed the bounds of data visualization; Tukey with his new statistical approach of exploratory data analysis and Tufte with his book "The Visual Display of Quantitative Information" paved the way for refining data visualization techniques for more than statisticians.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] With the progression of technology came the progression of data visualization; starting with hand-drawn visualizations and evolving into more technical applications – including interactive designs leading to software visualization.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The modern study of visualization started with computer graphics, which "has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] However, in its early days the lack of graphics power often limited its usefulness.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the special issue of Computer Graphics on Visualization in *Scientific Computing*.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Since then there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH".
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] They have been devoted to the general topics of data visualization, information visualization and scientific visualization, and more specific areas such as volume visualization.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Programs like SAS, SOFA, R, Minitab, Cornerstone and more allow for data visualization in the field of statistics.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Other data visualization applications, more focused and unique to individuals, programming languages such as D3, Python (through matplotlib, seaborn) and JavaScript and Java(through JavaFX) help to make the visualization of quantitative data a possibility.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Private schools have also developed programs to meet the demand for learning data visualization and associated programming libraries, including free programs like The Data Incubator or paid programs like General Assembly.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Beginning with the symposium "Data to Discovery" in 2013, ArtCenter College of Design, Caltech and JPL in Pasadena have run an annual program on interactive data visualization.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The program asks: How can interactive data visualization help scientists and engineers explore their data more effectively?
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] How can computing, design, and design thinking help maximize research results?
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] What methodologies are most effective for leveraging knowledge from these fields?
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] In recent years, with the increasing popularity of games, data and information visualization has been gradually applied in the gaming industry through the use of analytical tools to assess player statistics and game performance, which are visualized in the form of health points, maps, and diagrams.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The data is then collected and stored by developers.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The implementation of these tools in gaming assists developers in improving user experience and in the development and updating of newer games.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization involves specific terminology, some of which is derived from statistics.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The distinction between quantitative and categorical variables is important because the two types require different methods of visualization.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Two primary types of information displays are tables and graphs.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Eppler and Lengler have developed the "Periodic Table of Visualization Methods," an interactive chart displaying various data visualization methods.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] It includes six types of data visualization methods: data, information, concept, strategy, metaphor and compound.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Interactive data visualization has been a pursuit of statisticians since the late 1960s.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Examples of the developments can be found on the American Statistical Association video lending library.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] There are different approaches on the scope of data visualization.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] One common focus is on information presentation, such as Friedman (2008).
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Friendly (2008) presumes two main parts of data visualization: statistical graphics, and thematic cartography.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] All these subjects are closely related to graphic design and information representation.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Within The Harvard Business Review, Scott Berinato developed a framework to approach data visualisation.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] To start thinking visually, users must consider two questions; 1) What you have and 2) what you're doing.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] The first step is identifying what data you want visualised.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] It is data-driven like profit over the past ten years or a conceptual idea like how a specific organisation is structured.
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Once this question is answered one can then focus on whether they are trying to communicate information (declarative visualisation) or trying to figure something out (exploratory visualisation).
[src:plotly-python/data-visualization-p01] Scott Berinato combines these questions to give four types of visual communication that each have their own goals.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Visualization today has ever-expanding applications in science, education, engineering (e.g., product visualization), interactive multimedia, medicine, etc.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Typical of a visualization application is the field of computer graphics.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] The invention of computer graphics (and 3D computer graphics) may be the most important development in visualization since the invention of central perspective in the Renaissance period.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] The development of animation also helped advance visualization.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] The use of visualization to present information is not a new phenomenon.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] It has been used in maps, scientific drawings, and data plots for over a thousand years.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Examples from cartography include Ptolemy's Geographia (2nd century AD), a map of China (1137 AD), and Minard's map (1861) of Napoleon's invasion of Russia a century and a half ago.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Most of the concepts learned in devising these images carry over in a straightforward manner to computer visualization.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Edward Tufte has written three critically acclaimed books that explain many of these principles.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Computer graphics has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the publication of Visualization in Scientific Computing, a special issue of Computer Graphics.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Since then, there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH, devoted to the general topic, and special areas in the field, for example volume visualization.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Most people are familiar with the digital animations produced to present meteorological data during weather reports on television, though few can distinguish between those models of reality and the satellite photos that are also shown on such programs.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] TV also offers scientific visualizations when it shows computer drawn and animated reconstructions of road or airplane accidents.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Some of the most popular examples of scientific visualizations are computer-generated images that show real spacecraft in action, out in the void far beyond Earth, or on other planets.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Dynamic forms of visualization, such as educational animation or timelines, have the potential to enhance learning about systems that change over time.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Apart from the distinction between interactive visualizations and animation, the most useful categorization is probably between abstract and model-based scientific visualizations.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] The abstract visualizations show completely conceptual constructs in 2D or 3D.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] These generated shapes are completely arbitrary.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] The model-based visualizations either place overlays of data on real or digitally constructed images of reality or make a digital construction of a real object directly from the scientific data.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Scientific visualization is usually done with specialized software, though there are a few exceptions, noted below.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Some of these specialized programs have been released as open source software, having very often its origins in universities, within an academic environment where sharing software tools and giving access to the source code is common.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] There are also many proprietary software packages of scientific visualization tools.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Models and frameworks for building visualizations include the data flow models popularized by systems such as AVS, IRIS Explorer, and VTK toolkit, and data state models in spreadsheet systems such as the Spreadsheet for Visualization and Spreadsheet for Images.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] As a subject in computer science, scientific visualization is the use of interactive, sensory representations, typically visual, of abstract data to reinforce cognition, hypothesis building, and reasoning.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Scientific visualization is the transformation, selection, or representation of data from simulations or experiments, with an implicit or explicit geometric structure, to allow the exploration, analysis, and understanding of the data.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Scientific visualization focuses and emphasizes the representation of higher order data using primarily graphics and animation techniques.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] It is a very important part of visualization and maybe the first one, as the visualization of experiments and phenomena is as old as science itself.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Traditional areas of scientific visualization are flow visualization, medical visualization, astrophysical visualization, and chemical visualization.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] There are several different techniques to visualize scientific data, with isosurface reconstruction and direct volume rendering being the more common.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Data visualization is a related subcategory of visualization dealing with statistical graphics and geospatial data (as in thematic cartography) that is abstracted in schematic form.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Information visualization concentrates on the use of computer-supported tools to explore large amount of abstract data.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] The term "information visualization" was originally coined by the User Interface Research Group at Xerox PARC and included Jock Mackinlay.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Practical application of information visualization in computer programs involves selecting, transforming, and representing abstract data in a form that facilitates human interaction for exploration and understanding.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Important aspects of information visualization are dynamics of visual representation and the interactivity.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Strong techniques enable the user to modify the visualization in real-time, thus affording unparalleled perception of patterns and structural relations in the abstract data in question.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Educational visualization is using a simulation to create an image of something so it can be taught about.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] This is very useful when teaching about a topic that is difficult to otherwise see, for example, atomic structure, because atoms are far too small to be studied easily without expensive and difficult to use scientific equipment.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] The use of visual representations to transfer knowledge between at least two persons aims to improve the transfer of knowledge by using computer and non-computer-based visualization methods complementarily.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Thus properly designed visualization is an important part of not only data analysis but knowledge transfer process, too.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Knowledge transfer may be significantly improved using hybrid designs as it enhances information density but may decrease clarity as well.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] For example, visualization of a 3D scalar field may be implemented using iso-surfaces for field distribution and textures for the gradient of the field.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Examples of such visual formats are sketches, diagrams, images, objects, interactive visualizations, information visualization applications, and imaginary visualizations as in stories.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] While information visualization concentrates on the use of computer-supported tools to derive new insights, knowledge visualization focuses on transferring insights and creating new knowledge in groups.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Beyond the mere transfer of facts, knowledge visualization aims to further transfer insights, experiences, attitudes, values, expectations, perspectives, opinions, and estimates in different fields by using various complementary visualizations.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Product visualization involves visualization software technology for the viewing and manipulation of 3D models, technical drawing and other related documentation of manufactured components and large assemblies of products.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] It is a key part of product lifecycle management.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Product visualization software typically provides high levels of photorealism so that a product can be viewed before it is actually manufactured.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] This supports functions ranging from design and styling to sales and marketing.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] *Technical visualization* is an important aspect of product development.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Originally technical drawings were made by hand, but with the rise of advanced computer graphics the drawing board has been replaced by computer-aided design (CAD).
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] CAD-drawings and models have several advantages over hand-made drawings such as the possibility of 3-D modeling, rapid prototyping, and simulation.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] 3D product visualization promises more interactive experiences for online shoppers, but also challenges retailers to overcome hurdles in the production of 3D content, as large-scale 3D content production can be extremely costly and time-consuming.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] In recent years, product visualization has increasingly incorporated interactive and real-time technologies, particularly in e-commerce environments.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Modern 3D visualization tools enable users to explore products in detail, customize attributes such as color, materials, and configuration, and view items in simulated or real-world contexts.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] These capabilities enhance user engagement and support more informed decision-making by providing realistic and context-aware representations of products.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] As a result, product visualization can help reduce uncertainty prior to purchase and contribute to lower product return rates.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Visual communication is the communication of ideas through the visual display of information.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Primarily associated with two dimensional images, it includes: alphanumerics, art, signs, and electronic resources.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Recent research in the field has focused on web design and graphically oriented usability.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Visual analytics focuses on human interaction with visualization systems as part of a larger process of data analysis.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Visual analytics has been defined as "the science of analytical reasoning supported by the interactive visual interface".
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Its focus is on human information discourse (interaction) within massive, dynamically changing information spaces.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Visual analytics research concentrates on support for perceptual and cognitive operations that enable users to detect the expected and discover the unexpected in complex information spaces.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Technologies resulting from visual analytics find their application in almost all fields, but are being driven by critical needs (and funding) in biology and national security.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] One particular type of interactive visualization is virtual reality (VR), where the visual representation of information is presented using an immersive display device such as a stereo projector (see stereoscopy).
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Another type of interactive visualization is collaborative visualization, in which multiple people interact with the same computer visualization to communicate their ideas to each other or to explore information cooperatively.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Frequently, collaborative visualization is used when people are physically separated.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Using several networked computers, the same visualization can be presented to each person simultaneously.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] The people then make annotations to the visualization as well as communicate via audio (i.e., telephone), video (i.e., a video-conference), or text (i.e., IRC) messages.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] The Programmer's Hierarchical Interactive Graphics System (PHIGS) was one of the first programmatic efforts at interactive visualization and provided an enumeration of the types of input humans provide.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] All of these actions require a physical device.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Input devices range from the common – keyboards, mice, graphics tablets, trackballs, and touchpads – to the esoteric – wired gloves, boom arms, and even omnidirectional treadmills.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] These input actions can be used to control both the unique information being represented or the way that the information is presented.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] When the information being presented is altered, the visualization is usually part of a feedback loop.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] For example, consider an aircraft avionics system where the pilot inputs roll, pitch, and yaw and the visualization system provides a rendering of the aircraft's new attitude.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Another example would be a scientist who changes a simulation while it is running in response to a visualization of its current progress.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] This is called *computational steering*.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] More frequently, the representation of the information is changed rather than the information itself.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Experiments have shown that a delay of more than 20 ms between when input is provided and a visual representation is updated is noticeable by most people .
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Thus it is desirable for an interactive visualization to provide a rendering based on human input within this time frame.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] However, when large amounts of data must be processed to create a visualization, this becomes hard or even impossible with current technology.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Thus the term "interactive visualization" is usually applied to systems that provide feedback to users within several seconds of input.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] The term *interactive framerate* is often used to measure how interactive a visualization is.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Framerates measure the frequency with which an image (a frame) can be generated by a visualization system.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] A framerate of 50 frames per second (frame/s) is considered good while 0.1 frame/s would be considered poor.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] The use of framerates to characterize interactivity is slightly misleading however, since framerate is a measure of bandwidth while humans are more sensitive to latency.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Specifically, it is possible to achieve a good framerate of 50 frame/s but if the images generated refer to changes to the visualization that a person made more than 1 second ago, it will not feel interactive to a person.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] The rapid response time required for interactive visualization is a difficult constraint to meet and there are several approaches that have been explored to provide people with rapid visual feedback based on their input.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] *Progressive rendering* – where a framerate is guaranteed by rendering some subset of the information to be presented and providing incremental (progressive) improvements to the rendering once the visualization is no longer changing.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] *Level-of-detail (LOD) rendering* – where simplified representations of information are rendered to achieve a desired framerate while a person is providing input and then the full representation is used to generate a still image once the person is through manipulating the visualization.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] Subsampling can also be used to accelerate rendering techniques such as volume visualization that require more than twice the computations for an image twice the size.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] By rendering a smaller image and then scaling the image to fill the requested screen space, much less time is required to render the same data.
[src:plotly-python/interactive-visualization] *Frameless rendering* – where the visualization is no longer presented as a time series of images, but as a single image where different regions are updated over time.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Web browsers have a dedicated JavaScript engine that executes the client code.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] These engines are also utilized in some servers and a variety of apps.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The most popular runtime system for non-browser usage is Node.js.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] JavaScript is a high-level, often just-in-time–compiled language that conforms to the ECMAScript standard.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] It has dynamic typing, prototype-based object-orientation, and first-class functions.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] It is multi-paradigm, supporting event-driven, functional, and imperative programming styles.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] It has application programming interfaces (APIs) for working with text, dates, regular expressions, standard data structures, and the Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Although Java and JavaScript are similar in name and syntax, the two languages are distinct and differ greatly in design.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The first popular web browser with a graphical user interface, Mosaic, was released in 1993.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released a more polished browser, Netscape Navigator, in 1994.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] During these formative years of the Web, web pages could only be static, lacking the capability for dynamic behavior after the page was loaded in the browser.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] There was a desire in the flourishing web development scene to remove this limitation, so in 1995, Netscape decided to add a programming language to Navigator.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] They pursued two routes to achieve this: collaborating with Sun Microsystems to embed the Java language, while also hiring Brendan Eich to embed the Scheme language.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The goal was a "language for the masses", "to help nonprogrammers create dynamic, interactive Web sites".
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Netscape management soon decided that the best option was for Eich to devise a new language, with syntax similar to Java and less like Scheme or other extant scripting languages.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Although the new language and its interpreter implementation were called LiveScript when first shipped as part of a Navigator beta in September 1995, the name was changed to JavaScript for the official release in December.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The choice of the *JavaScript* name has caused confusion, implying that it is directly related to Java.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] At the time, the dot-com boom had begun and Java was a popular new language, so Eich considered the JavaScript name a marketing ploy by Netscape.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] On the JavaScript front, Microsoft created its own interpreter called JScript.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Microsoft first released JScript in 1996, alongside initial support for CSS and extensions to HTML.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Each of these implementations was noticeably different from their counterparts in Netscape Navigator.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] These differences made it difficult for developers to make their websites work well in both browsers, leading to widespread use of "best viewed in Netscape" and "best viewed in Internet Explorer" logos for several years.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] In November 1996, Netscape submitted JavaScript to Ecma International, as the starting point for a standard specification that all browser vendors could conform to.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] This led to the official release of the first ECMAScript language specification in June 1997.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The standards process continued for a few years, with the release of ECMAScript 2 in June 1998 and ECMAScript 3 in December 1999.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] However, the effort to fully standardize the language was undermined by Microsoft gaining an increasingly dominant position in the browser market.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] By the early 2000s, Internet Explorer's market share reached 95%.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] This meant that JScript became the de facto standard for client-side scripting on the Web.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Microsoft initially participated in the standards process and implemented some proposals in its JScript language, but eventually it stopped collaborating on ECMA work.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] During the period of Internet Explorer dominance in the early 2000s, client-side scripting was stagnant.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] This started to change in 2004, when the successor of Netscape, Mozilla, released the Firefox browser.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Firefox was well received by many, taking significant market share from Internet Explorer.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] In 2005, Mozilla joined ECMA International, and work started on the ECMAScript for XML (E4X) standard.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] This led to Mozilla working jointly with Macromedia (later acquired by Adobe Systems), who were implementing E4X in their ActionScript 3 language, which was based on an ECMAScript 4 draft.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The goal became standardizing ActionScript 3 as the new ECMAScript 4.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] To this end, Adobe Systems released the Tamarin implementation as an open source project.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] However, Tamarin and ActionScript 3 were too different from established client-side scripting, and without cooperation from Microsoft, ECMAScript 4 never reached fruition.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Meanwhile, very important developments were occurring in open-source communities not affiliated with ECMA work.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] In 2005, Jesse James Garrett released a white paper in which he coined the term Ajax and described a set of technologies, of which JavaScript was the backbone, to create web applications where data can be loaded in the background, avoiding the need for full page reloads.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] This sparked a renaissance period of JavaScript, spearheaded by open-source libraries and the communities that formed around them.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Many new libraries were created, including jQuery, Prototype, Dojo Toolkit, and MooTools.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, with the V8 JavaScript engine that was faster than its competition.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The key innovation was just-in-time compilation (JIT), so other browser vendors needed to overhaul their engines for JIT.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] In July 2008, these disparate parties came together for a conference in Oslo.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] This led to the eventual agreement in early 2009 to combine all relevant work and drive the language forward.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The result was the ECMAScript 5 standard, released in December 2009.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Ambitious work on the language continued for several years, culminating in an extensive collection of additions and refinements being formalized with the publication of ECMAScript 6 in 2015.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The creation of Node.js in 2009 by Ryan Dahl sparked a significant increase in the usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Node combines the V8 engine, an event loop, and I/O APIs, thereby providing a stand-alone JavaScript runtime system.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] As of 2018, Node had been used by millions of developers, and npm had the most modules of any package manager in the world.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The ECMAScript draft specification is currently maintained openly on GitHub, and editions are produced via regular annual snapshots.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Potential revisions to the language are vetted through a comprehensive proposal process.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Now, instead of edition numbers, developers check the status of upcoming features individually.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The current JavaScript ecosystem has many libraries and frameworks, established programming practices, and substantial usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Plus, with the rise of single-page applications and other JavaScript-heavy websites, several transpilers have been created to aid the development process.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] As of 2025, the overwhelming majority of websites (98.9%) use JavaScript for client side webpage behavior.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] "JavaScript" is a trademark of Oracle Corporation in the United States.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The trademark was originally issued to Sun Microsystems on 6 May 1997, and was transferred to Oracle when they acquired Sun in 2009.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] A letter was circulated in September 2024, spearheaded by Ryan Dahl, calling on Oracle to free the JavaScript trademark.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Brendan Eich, the original creator of JavaScript, was among the over 14,000 signatories who supported the initiative.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] JavaScript is the dominant client-side scripting language of the Web, with 99% of all websites using it for this purpose.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Scripts are embedded in or included from HTML documents and interact with the DOM.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] All major web browsers have a built-in JavaScript engine that executes the code on the user's device.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Over 80% of websites use a third-party JavaScript library or web framework as part of their client-side scripting.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Other notable ones include Angular, Bootstrap, Lodash, Modernizr, React, Underscore, and Vue.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Multiple options can be used in conjunction, such as jQuery and Bootstrap.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] However, the term "Vanilla JS" was coined for websites not using any libraries or frameworks at all, instead relying entirely on standard JavaScript functionality.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The use of JavaScript has expanded beyond its web browser roots.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] JavaScript engines are now embedded in a variety of other software systems, both for server-side website deployments and non-browser applications.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Initial attempts at promoting server-side JavaScript usage were Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's Internet Information Services, but they were small niches.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Server-side usage eventually started to grow in the late 2000s, with the creation of Node.js and other approaches.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Electron, Cordova, React Native, and other application frameworks have been used to create many applications with behavior implemented in JavaScript.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Other non-browser applications include Adobe Acrobat support for scripting PDF documents and GNOME Shell extensions written in JavaScript.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Oracle used to provide Nashorn, a JavaScript interpreter, as part of their Java Development Kit (JDK) API library along with **jjs** a command line interpreter as of JDK version 8.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] As a replacement Oracle offered GraalJS which can also be used with the OpenJDK which allows one to create and reference Java objects in JavaScript code and add runtime scripting in JavaScript to applications written in Java.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] JavaScript has been used in some embedded systems, usually by leveraging Node.js.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] A JavaScript engine must be embedded within a runtime system (such as a web browser or a standalone system) to enable scripts to interact with the broader environment.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The runtime system includes the necessary APIs for input/output operations, such as networking, storage, and graphics, and provides the ability to import scripts.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The runtime processes messages from a queue one at a time, and it calls a function associated with each new message, creating a call stack frame with the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The call stack shrinks and grows based on the function's needs.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] When the call stack is empty upon function completion, JavaScript proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] This is called the event loop, described as "run to completion" because each message is fully processed before the next message is considered.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] However, the language's concurrency model describes the event loop as non-blocking: program I/O is performed using events and callback functions.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] This means, for example, that JavaScript can process a mouse click while waiting for a database query to return information.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The notable standalone runtimes are Node.js, Deno, and Bun.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The following features are common to all conforming ECMAScript implementations unless explicitly specified otherwise.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The number of cited reserved words including keywords is 50–60 and varies depending on the implementation.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] JavaScript supports much of the structured programming syntax from C (e.g., `if` statements, `while` loops, `switch` statements, `do while` loops, etc.).
[src:plotly-python/javascript] One partial exception is scoping: originally JavaScript only had function scoping with `var`; block scoping was added in ECMAScript 2015 with the keywords `let` and `const`.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Like C, JavaScript makes a distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] One syntactic difference from C is automatic semicolon insertion, which allow semicolons (which terminate statements) to be omitted.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] JavaScript is weakly typed, which means certain types are implicitly cast depending on the operation used.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Values are cast to numbers by casting to strings and then casting the strings to numbers.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] These processes can be modified by defining `toString` and `valueOf` functions on the prototype for string and number casting respectively.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] JavaScript has received criticism for the way it implements these conversions as the complexity of the rules can be mistaken for inconsistency.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] For example, when adding a number to a string, the number will be cast to a string before performing concatenation, but when subtracting a number from a string, the string is cast to a number before performing subtraction.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Often also mentioned is `{} + []` resulting in `0` (number).
[src:plotly-python/javascript] This is misleading: the `{}` is interpreted as an empty code block instead of an empty object, and the empty array is cast to a number by the remaining unary `+` operator.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] If the expression is wrapped in parentheses - `({} + [])` – the curly brackets are interpreted as an empty object and the result of the expression is `"[object Object]"` as expected.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] JavaScript is dynamically typed like most other scripting languages.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] A type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] For example, a variable initially bound to a number may be reassigned to a string.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] JavaScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] JavaScript includes an `eval` function that can execute statements provided as strings at run-time.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] In JavaScript, an object is an associative array, augmented with a prototype (see below); each key provides the name for an object property, and there are two syntactical ways to specify such a name: dot notation (`obj.x = 10`) and bracket notation (`obj["x"] = 10`).
[src:plotly-python/javascript] A property may be added, rebound, or deleted at run-time.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Most properties of an object (and any property that belongs to an object's prototype inheritance chain) can be enumerated using a `for...in` loop.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] JavaScript uses prototypes where many other object-oriented languages use classes for inheritance, but it's still possible to simulate most class-based features with the prototype system.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Additionally, ECMAScript version 6 (released June 2015) introduced the keywords **class**, **extends** and **super**, which serve as syntactic sugar to abstract the underlying prototypal inheritance system with a more conventional interface.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Constructors are declared by specifying a method named **constructor**, and all classes are automatically subclasses of the base class Object, similarly to Java.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Though the underlying object mechanism is still based on prototypes, the newer syntax is similar to other object oriented languages.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Private variables are declared by prefixing the field name with a number sign (#), and polymorphism is not directly supported, although it can be emulated by manually calling different functions depending on the number and type of arguments provided.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Functions double as object constructors, along with their typical role.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Prefixing a function call with *new* will create an instance of a prototype, inheriting properties and methods from the constructor (including properties from the `Object` prototype).
[src:plotly-python/javascript] ECMAScript 5 offers the `Object.create` method, allowing explicit creation of an instance without automatically inheriting from the `Object` prototype (older environments can assign the prototype to `null`).
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The constructor's `prototype` property determines the object used for the new object's internal prototype.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] New methods can be added by modifying the prototype of the function used as a constructor.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] JavaScript's built-in classes, such as `Array` and `Object`, also have prototypes that can be modified.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] However, it's generally considered bad practice to modify built-in objects, because third-party code may use or inherit methods and properties from these objects, and may not expect the prototype to be modified.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Unlike in many object-oriented languages, in JavaScript there is no distinction between a function definition and a method definition.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Rather, the distinction occurs during function calling.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] When a function is called as a method of an object, the function's local *this* keyword is bound to that object for that invocation.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] JavaScript functions are first-class; a function is considered to be an object.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] As such, a function may have properties and methods, such as `.call()` and `.bind()`.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] A *nested* function is a function defined within another function.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] It is created each time the outer function is invoked.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] In addition, each nested function forms a lexical closure: the lexical scope of the outer function (including any constant, local variable, or argument value) becomes part of the internal state of each inner function object, even after execution of the outer function concludes.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] JavaScript also supports anonymous functions.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] JavaScript supports implicit and explicit delegation.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] JavaScript natively supports various function-based implementations of Role patterns like Traits and Mixins.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Such a function defines additional behavior by at least one method bound to the `this` keyword within its `function` body.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] A Role then has to be delegated explicitly via `call` or `apply` to objects that need to feature additional behavior that is not shared via the prototype chain.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Whereas explicit function-based delegation does cover composition in JavaScript, implicit delegation already happens every time the prototype chain is walked in order to, e.g., find a method that might be related to but is not directly owned by an object.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Once the method is found it gets called within this object's context.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Thus inheritance in JavaScript is covered by a delegation automatism that is bound to the prototype property of constructor functions.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] An indefinite number of parameters can be passed to a function.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The function can access them through formal parameters and also through the local `arguments` object.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Variadic functions can also be created by using the `bind` method.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Like in many scripting languages, arrays and objects (associative arrays in other languages) can each be created with a succinct shortcut syntax.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] In fact, these literals form the basis of the JSON data format.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] JavaScript supports regular expressions for text searches and manipulation.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] A built-in Promise object provides functionality for handling promises and associating handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual result.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] JavaScript supplies combinator methods, which allow developers to combine multiple JavaScript promises and do operations based on different scenarios.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The methods introduced are: Promise.race, Promise.all, Promise.allSettled and Promise.any.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Async/await allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written, with minimal overhead, structured similarly to traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Variables in JavaScript can be defined using either the `var`, `let` or `const` keywords.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Variables defined without keywords will be defined at the global scope.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Arrow functions were first introduced in 6th Edition – ECMAScript 2015.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] They shorten the syntax for writing functions in JavaScript.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Arrow functions are anonymous, so a variable is needed to refer to them in order to invoke them after their creation, unless surrounded by parenthesis and executed immediately.
