[src:plotly-python/javascript] Note the comments in the examples above, all of which were preceded with two forward slashes.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] More examples can be found at the Wikibooks page on JavaScript syntax examples.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] JavaScript and the DOM provide the potential for malicious authors to deliver scripts to run on a client computer via the Web.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Browser authors minimize this risk using two restrictions.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] First, scripts run in a sandbox in which they can only perform Web-related actions, not general-purpose programming tasks like creating files.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Second, scripts are constrained by the same-origin policy: scripts from one website do not have access to information such as usernames, passwords, or cookies sent to another site.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Most JavaScript-related security bugs are breaches of either the same origin policy or the sandbox.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] There are subsets of general JavaScript—ADsafe, Secure ECMAScript (SES)—that provide greater levels of security, especially on code created by third parties (such as advertisements).
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Closure Toolkit is another project for safe embedding and isolation of third-party JavaScript and HTML.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Content Security Policy is the main intended method of ensuring that only trusted code is executed on a Web page.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] A common JavaScript-related security problem is cross-site scripting (XSS), a violation of the same-origin policy.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker can cause a target Website, such as an online banking website, to include a malicious script in the webpage presented to a victim.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The script in this example can then access the banking application with the privileges of the victim, potentially disclosing secret information or transferring money without the victim's authorization.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] One important solution to XSS vulnerabilities is HTML sanitization.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Some browsers include partial protection against *reflected* XSS attacks, in which the attacker provides a URL including malicious script.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] However, even users of those browsers are vulnerable to other XSS attacks, such as those where the malicious code is stored in a database.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Only correct design of Web applications on the server-side can fully prevent XSS.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities can also occur because of implementation mistakes by browser authors.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Another cross-site vulnerability is cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:plotly-python/javascript] In CSRF, code on an attacker's site tricks the victim's browser into taking actions the user did not intend at a target site (like transferring money at a bank).
[src:plotly-python/javascript] When target sites rely solely on cookies for request authentication, requests originating from code on the attacker's site can carry the same valid login credentials of the initiating user.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] In general, the solution to CSRF is to require an authentication value in a hidden form field, and not only in the cookies, to authenticate any request that might have lasting effects.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Checking the HTTP Referrer header can also help.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] "JavaScript hijacking" is a type of CSRF attack in which a `<script>` tag on an attacker's site exploits a page on the victim's site that returns private information such as JSON or JavaScript.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Developers of client-server applications must recognize that untrusted clients may be under the control of attackers.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The author of an application should not assume that their JavaScript code will run as intended (or at all) because any secret embedded in the code could be extracted by a determined adversary.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Package management systems such as npm and Bower are popular with JavaScript developers.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Such systems allow a developer to easily manage their program's dependencies upon other developers' program libraries.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Developers trust that the maintainers of the libraries will keep them secure and up to date, but that is not always the case.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] A vulnerability has emerged because of this blind trust.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Relied-upon libraries can have new releases that cause bugs or vulnerabilities to appear in all programs that rely upon the libraries.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Inversely, a library can go unpatched with known vulnerabilities out in the wild.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] In a study done looking over a sample of 133,000 websites, researchers found 37% of the websites included a library with at least one known vulnerability.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] This occurred in March 2016 when Azer Koçulu removed his repository from npm.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] This caused tens of thousands of programs and websites depending upon his libraries to break.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] JavaScript provides an interface to a wide range of browser capabilities, some of which may have flaws such as buffer overflows.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] These flaws can allow attackers to write scripts that would run any code they wish on the user's system.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] This code is not by any means limited to another JavaScript application.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] For example, a buffer overrun exploit can allow an attacker to gain access to the operating system's API with superuser privileges.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] These flaws have affected major browsers including Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Safari.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Plugins, such as video players, Adobe Flash, and the wide range of ActiveX controls enabled by default in Microsoft Internet Explorer, may also have flaws exploitable via JavaScript (such flaws have been exploited in the past).
[src:plotly-python/javascript] In Windows Vista, Microsoft has attempted to contain the risks of bugs such as buffer overflows by running the Internet Explorer process with limited privileges.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Google Chrome similarly confines its page renderers to their own "sandbox".
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Web browsers are capable of running JavaScript outside the sandbox, with the privileges necessary to, for example, create or delete files.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Such privileges are not intended to be granted to code from the Web.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Incorrectly granting privileges to JavaScript from the Web has played a role in vulnerabilities in both Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] In Windows XP Service Pack 2, Microsoft demoted JScript's privileges in Internet Explorer.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Microsoft Windows allows JavaScript source files on a computer's hard drive to be launched as general-purpose, non-sandboxed programs (see: Windows Script Host).
[src:plotly-python/javascript] This makes JavaScript (like VBScript) a theoretically viable vector for a Trojan horse, although JavaScript Trojan horses are uncommon in practice.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] In 2015, a JavaScript-based proof-of-concept implementation of a rowhammer attack was described in a paper by security researchers.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] In 2017, a JavaScript-based attack via browser was demonstrated that could bypass ASLR.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] In 2018, the paper that announced the Spectre attacks against Speculative Execution in Intel and other processors included a JavaScript implementation.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Important tools have evolved with the language.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] A common misconception is that JavaScript is directly related to Java.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Both indeed have a C-like syntax (the C language being their most immediate common ancestor language).
[src:plotly-python/javascript] They are also typically sandboxed, and JavaScript was designed with Java's syntax and standard library in mind.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] In particular, all Java keywords were reserved in original JavaScript, JavaScript's standard library follows Java's naming conventions, and JavaScript's `Math` and `Date` objects are based on classes from Java 1.0.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Both languages first appeared in 1995, but Java was developed by James Gosling of Sun Microsystems and JavaScript by Brendan Eich of Netscape Communications.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] The differences between the two languages are more prominent than their similarities.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Java has static typing, while JavaScript's typing is dynamic.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Java is loaded from compiled bytecode, while JavaScript is loaded as human-readable source code.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Java's objects are class-based, while JavaScript's are prototype-based.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Finally, Java did not support functional programming until Java 8, while JavaScript has done so from the beginning, being influenced by Scheme.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] JSON is a data format derived from JavaScript; hence the name JavaScript Object Notation.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] It is a widely used format supported by many other programming languages.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] Many websites are JavaScript-heavy, so transpilers have been created to convert code written in other languages, which can aid the development process.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] TypeScript and CoffeeScript are two notable languages that transpile to JavaScript.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] WebAssembly is a newer language with a bytecode format designed to complement JavaScript, especially the performance-critical portions of web page scripts.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] All of the major JavaScript engines support WebAssembly, which runs in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:plotly-python/javascript] asm.js is a subset of JavaScript that served as the forerunner of WebAssembly.
[src:plotly-python/plotly-express] Plotly Express is a terse, consistent, high-level API for creating figures.
[src:plotly-python/plotly-express] Plotly Studio: Transform any dataset into an interactive data application in minutes with AI.
[src:plotly-python/plotly-express] The `plotly.express` module (usually imported as `px`) contains functions that can create entire figures at once, and is referred to as Plotly Express or PX.
[src:plotly-python/plotly-express] Plotly Express is a built-in part of the `plotly` library, and is the recommended starting point for creating most common figures.
[src:plotly-python/plotly-express] Every Plotly Express function uses graph objects internally and returns a `plotly.graph_objects.Figure` instance.
[src:plotly-python/plotly-express] Throughout the `plotly` documentation, you will find the Plotly Express way of building figures at the top of any applicable page, followed by a section on how to use graph objects to build similar figures.
[src:plotly-python/plotly-express] Any figure created in a single function call with Plotly Express could be created using graph objects alone, but with between 5 and 100 times more code.
[src:plotly-python/plotly-express] Plotly Express provides more than 30 functions for creating different types of figures.
[src:plotly-python/plotly-express] The API for these functions was carefully designed to be as consistent and easy to learn as possible, making it easy to switch from a scatter plot to a bar chart to a histogram to a sunburst chart throughout a data exploration session.
[src:plotly-python/plotly-express] Dash is the best way to build analytical apps in Python using Plotly figures.
[src:plotly-python/plotly-express] To run the app below, run `pip install dash`, click "Download" to get the code and run `python app.py`.
