[src:plotly-python/plotly] Plotly was founded by Alex Johnson, Jack Parmer, Chris Parmer, and Matthew Sundquist.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] The founders' backgrounds are in science, energy, and data analysis and visualization.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] Early employees include Christophe Viau, a Canadian software engineer and Ben Postlethwaite, a Canadian geophysicist.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] Plotly was named one of the Top 20 Hottest Innovative Companies in Canada by the Canadian Innovation Exchange.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] Plotly was featured in "startup row" at PyCon 2013, and sponsored the SciPy 2018 conference.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] Plotly raised $5.5 million during its Series A funding, led by MHS Capital, Siemens Venture Capital, Rho Ventures, Real Ventures, and Silicon Valley Bank.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] The Boston Globe and Washington Post newsrooms have produced data journalism using Plotly.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] In 2020, Plotly was named a Best Place to Work by the Canadian SME National Business Awards, and nominated as Business of the Year.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] Plotly offers open-source and enterprise products.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] Dash is a Python framework built on top of React, a JavaScript library.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] Dash also works for R, and most recently supports Julia.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] It is possible to integrate D3.js charts as Dash components.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] Dash provides the default CSS (plus HTML and JavaScript), but for custom styling Dash applications, CSS can be added, or Dash Enterprise used.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] Dash Enterprise is Plotly's paid product for building, testing, deploying, managing and scaling Dash applications organization-wide.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] The product integrates with enterprise IT systems to enable organizations to build, deploy and scale low-code Dash applications.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] With open-source Dash, analytic applications can be run from a local machine, but cannot be easily accessed by others in the organization.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] Dash Enterprise installs on cloud environments and on-premises.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] Amazon Web Services, Google Cloud Platform, and Microsoft Azure are supported, as are multiple Linux on-premises servers.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] Authentication integrations include LDAP, AD, PKI, Okta, SAML, OAuth2, SSO, and email authentication, and Dash application access is managed through a GUI rather than code.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] Dash Enterprise connects to major big data backends, including Salesforce, PostgreSQL, Databricks via PySpark, Snowflake, Dask, Datashader, and Vaex.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] In 2020, Plotly partnered with NVIDIA to integrate Dash with RAPIDS, and NVIDIA participated in Plotly's Series C funding round.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] Dash Enterprise enables low-code development of Dash applications, which is not possible with open-source Dash.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] Enterprise users can write applications in multiple development environments, including Jupyter Notebook.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] Dash Enterprise ships with several “development engines” for drag-and-drop application editing, application design, and automated reporting, as well as dozens of artificial intelligence and machine learning application templates.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] Dash application code is deployed to Dash Enterprise using the git-push command.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] Dash application deployments are containerized to avoid dependency conflicts, and can be embedded in existing web platforms without iframes.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] Deployed applications can be managed and accessed in a single portal called App Manager, where administrators can control user authentication and view usage analytics.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] Dash Enterprise scales horizontally with Kubernetes.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] Jobs queuing, GPU acceleration, and CPU parallelization support high performance computing requirements.
[src:plotly-python/plotly] Plotly also offers professional services for application development and workshop training.
